// Simulates the interaction between light rays and microfacets on surfaces.

// Changes: ------------------------------------
//
//     - Fixed self-shadowing bug that occurs when viewing the
//       microfacet surface from below or along the horizon.
//     - Fixed sampling on blue noise - it is now "nearest"
//       instead of "bilinear".

// Controls: ------------------------------------
//
// Mouse click and drag : Change light direction.
//
// To change the bumpmap:
//
//     1. Navigate to Buffer A.
//     2. Change IChannel0 to a different texture.
//     3. Restart the shader.
//
//     You'll notice that the specular highlights will
//     be sensitive to the distribution of 
//     intensity gradients on the texture you choose.
//
// To change the smoothness:
//
//     1. Navigate to Buffer A.
//     2. Scroll to the top.
//     3. Find a variable called "anisotropicSmoothness".
//     4. Change the value for horizontal and vertical smoothness.
//     5. Do not use the value 0! (Otherwise you'll divide by 0.)
//     6. Compile.
//     7. Restart the shader.
//
//     Note that if you make the smoothness too small,
//     the raymarcher might miss some facets when
//     the angle is nearly parallel,
//     which will break self-shadowing.
//
// To view the underlying microfacet structure:
// 
//     1. Navigate to Buffer A.
//     2. Change USE_NOISE to 0.
//     3. Compile.
//     4. Restart the shader.
//     5. Pause the shader.
//     6. Click to reroll a microfacet structure sample.
//     7. Unpause to see the undithered samples converge.
//     
//     You'll see the microfacet surface that is being traced against.
//     This surface is normally different per pixel, per frame.

// How it works: ------------------------------------
//
//     1.  Raytrace a scene in a typical way:
//         Get hits for a plane and a sphere.
//
//     2.  Create a "microfacet surface" at the hit point, 
//         aligned to the normal, and trace against it.
//         This surface contains a bump map and will be used
//         to calculate what normal direction is visible
//         from our view.
//
//     3.  Trace from the microfacet hit point to the light,
//         for self-shadowing.
//
//     The microfacet surface sample varies per pixel, per frame.
//     We're integrating over the entire bumpmap, 
//     and these facets are treated as infinitesimally small.
//
//     The lighting model used by individual facets is also
//     physically based. The intention is to compound
//     their effects by starting with an already good
//     microfacet approximation.

// Future work: ------------------------------------
//
// I'd like to "bake" the results of this into a lookup table.
// Perhaps one could provide the dot products between:
//     - Normal direction
//     - Tangent direction
//     - Light direction
//     - View direction
// 
// (This would be a 4 dimensional function). 
//
// Given these dot products, one could look up the value needed
// from a lookup table.
//
// Then I'd like to fit curves to this function to remove the need
// for a lookup table altogether.

// Interesting stuff I noticed: ------------------------------------
//
//     - It looks like the specular pattern resembles
//       the fourier spectrum of the bumpmap.

void mainImage( out vec4 fragColor, in vec2 fragCoord )
{
    fragColor = texture(iChannel0, fragCoord / iResolution.xy, 0.125);
    fragColor /= fragColor.a;

    fragColor.rgb = linearToGamma(fragColor.rgb);
    fragColor.rgb /= (0.5 + fragColor.rgb);
    fragColor.rgb = smoothstep(vec3(0), vec3(1), fragColor.rgb);
}

