// Flying a circle through two orthogonal starfields in the 4-D spacetime described by 
// Greg Egan in his Orthogonal series.
//
// The universe rendered here is mostly accurate to the one described by Greg Egan in his Orthogonal 
// series.
//
// This scene shows a universe with 4 dimensions, much like our own, except that there is no special
// "time" dimension. Objects are free to move in any direction (Always with a velocity of 1).
// For any given observer, their direction of motion dictates their own arrow of time.
//
// Stars are modelled as infinitely long 4-d lines. Because these lines are not parallel (The stars
// are moving), the 3-D domain repetition is a bit of a hack and sometimes ends up cutting off parts
// of stars. It only works well when the stars' arrows of time are approximately parallel.
// 
// One consequence of this universe is that the speed of light depends on its wavelength (which
// depends on its orientation relative to you). This creates the streaks seen behind the stars.
// For the sake of accuracy, rendering is done by sampling light is sampled at a few different 
// wavelength ranges. This also contributes to slow rendering.
//
// Another consequence is that a constantly accelerating object will eventually have a direction
// orthogonal to its original direction, which would appear to a stationary observer like moving at an
// infinite velocity.
//
// For a more complete explaination of the physics/geometry of Riemmanian spacetime,
// see http://gregegan.net/ORTHOGONAL/ORTHOGONAL.html



// ------------------------------------------ SETTINGS ------------------------------------------
// More stars & less artifacts - uncomment if your computer can handle it
//#define HIGH_QUALITY

// Less stars and more performance
//#define POTATO_QUALITY

// Controls how long star trails are.
#define STAR_VELOCITY 0.05

